        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "8bcb721aae9f6ddc",
        "text": "Thinking of inquiry as something we 'do' (eg, when we do a\n''\nunit of inquiry on Thursday afternoon) is problematic. Teachers\nare familiar with the concept of a cycle or framework for inquiry\nthat helps us design an ongoing journey of learning for students\n- often over several weeks. Tasks are organized around a broad\n''\nsequence of phases that moves students from an exploration\nof their prior knowledge through to deeper understanding as\na result of research, analysis and synthesis. This process is generally framed by questions generated by both teachers and students. This cycle can be applied to short and long-term investigations. The use of inquiry as a planning framework for such units is powerful and effective; however, when we see it only in this context we run the risk of treating it like a separate subject in the curriculum (see chapter 5 for more on inquiry frameworks).\n"
